<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-09-15T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-09-15T04:00:00-05:00" n="367" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">393.1115/838: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-09-15T17:00:00+08:00">September 15, 1937—5
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received September 15—10:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>662. Your [<hi rend="italic">Shanghai’s</hi>] 793 [<hi rend="italic">693</hi>], September 13, noon. Please inform Japanese Consul when
                            giving him information contained in Hankow’s September 14, 4 p.m.,<note n="33" xml:id="d367fn33">Quoted in Department’s telegram No. 207,
                                September 14, 8 p.m., <ref target="#pg_327">p. 327</ref>.</note>
                            that Hankow will continue to send American citizens on down trains of
                            Canton–Hankow line and that it is our hope that Japanese will do nothing
                            to make this impossible.</p>
                        <p>Sent to Shanghai, Hankow.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Johnson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>